🚀 Project Summary: Scalable Online Store Platform

I am building a functional online store platform that sells premium third-party products. The goal is to launch quickly with a simple, reliable structure, while designing the system to scale later into a multi-store and multi-warehouse architecture.

🎯 Core Objectives

Launch fast (functional > perfect)

Centralized control and tracking

Role-based access (customer, admin, staff)

Scalable to multiple stores and warehouses

Intelligent order routing to the closest store

🛒 Customer Flow

Customer signs up / logs in

Customer browses products

Adds products to cart

Proceeds to checkout

Enters delivery address

Makes payment

Order is created and assigned to a store

Store packs, labels, dispatches, and confirms delivery

🏬 Business Flow

Store receives assigned order

Staff picks products from inventory

Packages and labels order

Dispatches for delivery

Updates order status

Central system tracks all activities

🧠 Architecture Plan
Tech Stack

Next.js → Frontend + API routes + business logic

Supabase → Authentication + PostgreSQL database + security (RLS)

Stripe (later) → Payment processing

Vercel → Hosting

🗄 Core Database Structure

profiles (linked to Supabase auth)

stores

products

inventory

orders

order_items

addresses

System is centralized, but each order is assigned a store_id.

🔐 Roles

customer → Shop & track orders

staff → Manage assigned store orders

admin → Full system visibility

Routing is handled after login using role-based redirection from a single authentication endpoint.

🔮 Future Scalability

The system must support:

Multiple stores

Multiple warehouses

Automatic routing of orders to nearest store using latitude/longitude

Inventory separation per store

Centralized analytics and oversight

Routing logic:

Calculate customer location

Determine nearest store

Assign order automatically

Fallback if inventory unavailable

🧩 System Responsibility Split

Supabase → Authentication, database, security policies

Next.js → API endpoints, business logic, routing, UI

Central database → All stores connected to one core system

📌 Guiding Principle

Keep it simple for launch, but architected so scaling requires adding data — not rewriting the system.